<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>373</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-001U</addr>  <route>axt-001U.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="samson-abramsky.xml" type="local">Samson Abramsky</link></author><author><link href="achim-jung.xml" type="local">Achim Jung</link></author> </authors> <title>Basis for a dcpo</title> <meta name="source"><b>Defn 2.2.3</b> of <link href="abramsky-jung-domain-theory-1995.xml" type="local" title="Domain Theory">Abramsky and Jung</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  Let <tex>D</tex> be a dcpo and let <tex>\Downarrow (x)</tex> denote the set
  <tex>\{  y  \in  D  \mid  y  \ll  x  \}</tex>.
</p><p>  A subset <tex>B  \subseteq  D</tex> forms a basis for <tex>D</tex> if for every element <tex>x  \in   D</tex> the set <tex display="block">B_x  \vcentcolon \equiv   \Downarrow (x)  \cap  B</tex> contains a directed
  subset with supremum <tex>x</tex></p><p>  Elements of <tex>x</tex> are caled approximants to <tex>x</tex> relative to <tex>B</tex>.
</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>374</anchor>   <addr>axt-002L</addr>  <route>axt-002L.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="ayberkt.xml" type="local">Ayberk Tosun</link></author> <contributor><link href="martin-escardo.xml" type="local">Mart√≠n H. Escard√≥</link></contributor><contributor><link href="tom-de-jong.xml" type="local">Tom de Jong</link></contributor></authors> <title>Preliminary order-theoretic terminology in UF</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  In our presentation here, we decouple the notion of a basis for a
  <link href="axt-0021.xml" type="local" title="V-dcpo"><tex>\mathcal{V}</tex>-dcpo</link> from any kind of compactness or relative compactness
  requirements.
</p><p>  In the context of domain theory, the natural notion of basis <em>should</em>  include such requirements (see for example <link href="axt-001U.xml" type="local" title="Basis for a dcpo"><b>Defn. 2.2.3</b> of Abramsky and
  Jung</link>). As our presentation here is intended to be applicable to a
  class of lattices broader than that of dcpos, however, we attempt to keep the
  presentation free of bias towards a specific
  <link href="https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/concept+with+an+attitude" type="external">attitude</link>. This is
  our motivation for the aforementioned decoupling.
</p><p>  When the notion of a <link href="axt-0021.xml" type="local" title="V-dcpo"><tex>\mathcal{V}</tex>-dcpo</link> attains a specific
  <link href="https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/concept+with+an+attitude" type="external">attitude</link>, such as
  <link href="axt-0003.xml" type="local" title="Intuition on the notion of a domain">that of a denotational domain</link>, it is perfectly fine for these
  terms to be overloaded to refer to concepts that include these requirements.
</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>375</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-0022</addr>  <route>axt-0022.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="tom-de-jong.xml" type="local">Tom de Jong</link></author><author><link href="martin-escardo.xml" type="local">Mart√≠n H. Escard√≥</link></author><author><link href="ayberkt.xml" type="local">Ayberk Tosun</link></author> </authors> <title>Intensional basis for a <tex>\mathcal{V}</tex>-dcpo</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  Let <tex>D</tex> be a <link href="axt-0021.xml" type="local" title="V-dcpo"><tex>\mathcal{V}</tex>-dcpo</link>. An <em>intensional basis for <tex>D</tex></em> is a
  <link href="axt-001F.xml" type="local" title="ùì•-Family"><tex>\mathcal{V}</tex>-family</link> <tex>(B,  \beta )</tex> on <tex>D</tex> satisfying the condition: for every
  element <tex>x : D</tex>, there is a specified directed <link href="axt-001F.xml" type="local" title="ùì•-Family"><tex>\mathcal{V}</tex>-family</link>  <tex>(I_x,  \iota _x)</tex> on the basis index <tex>B</tex> such that
  <tex>x =  \bigvee  (I_x,  \beta   \circ   \iota _x).</tex></p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>376</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-0028</addr>  <route>axt-0028.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>28</day></date> <authors><author><link href="tom-de-jong.xml" type="local">Tom de Jong</link></author><author><link href="martin-escardo.xml" type="local">Mart√≠n H. Escard√≥</link></author><author><link href="ayberkt.xml" type="local">Ayberk Tosun</link></author> </authors> <title>Extensional basis for a <tex>\mathcal{V}</tex>-dcpo</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  Let <tex>D</tex> be a <link href="axt-0021.xml" type="local" title="V-dcpo"><tex>\mathcal{V}</tex>-dcpo</link>. An <em>intensional basis</em> <tex>(B,  \beta )</tex>  for <tex>D</tex> is called an <link href="axt-0022.xml" type="local" title="Intensional basis for a V-dcpo">extensional basis</link> if <tex>\beta</tex> is an
  embedding.
</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>377</anchor>  <taxon>Reference</taxon> <addr>abramsky-jung-domain-theory-1995</addr>  <route>abramsky-jung-domain-theory-1995.xml</route> <date><year>1995</year>  </date> <authors><author>Samson Abramsky</author><author>Achim Jung</author> </authors> <title>Domain Theory</title> <meta name="bibtex">@inbook{abramsky-jung-domain-theory-1995,
